---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

// About Stacey — the longer page. Family origin story, philosophy,
// who this is for. Wider measure for narrative breathing.
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About Stacey"
  description="About Stacey — the financial coach behind Yellow Legal Pad. Her father, her path, and how she works."
>
  <section class="section" aria-labelledby="story-heading">
    <div class="column-wide">
      <h1 id="story-heading">A yellow legal pad and a kitchen table</h1>
      <p class="dek">Financial coaching for life's biggest transitions.</p>

      <!-- Image slot — pending warm abstract imagery from Stacey
           (legal pad and pen, desk scene, natural textures; no
           stock photos of women). See TODO_STACEY.md § Brand
           imagery. Uncomment alongside the Pass 459 follow-up.
      <figure class="page-image">
        <img src="/images/about-hero.jpg" alt="" />
      </figure>
      -->

      <p>
        Stacey's father was the family's go-to person on money for
        decades. He had no credentials and no brokerage. What
        he had was a yellow legal pad, a felt-tip pen, and the belief
        that money was something you worked through with people, not
        at them.
      </p>

      <p>
        Anyone could ask. Cousins, neighbors, the woman who cut his
        hair, the guy who fixed his car. He'd pull out the pad, write
        down what was happening in plain English, and stay at the
        kitchen table until the numbers stopped feeling like an
        emergency.
      </p>

      <p>
        He wasn't optimizing returns or selling products. He was
        sitting with people. Nobody was bad at money, he believed
        &mdash; they'd just never been allowed to look at it without
        flinching.
      </p>

      <p>
        Stacey grew up watching that. The practice she runs today is
        carrying it forward.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* "How she got here" section is held until Stacey provides the
      copy. Restore when the text arrives:

      <section class="section" aria-labelledby="path-heading">
        <div class="column-wide">
          <h2 id="path-heading">How she got here</h2>
          <p>[Stacey's path — career, what led her to coaching.]</p>
          <p>[What she does NOT do — flat fee, not a registered advisor.]</p>
        </div>
      </section>
  */}

  <hr class="section-rule" />

  <section class="section">
    <div class="column">
      <p>
        Most people aren't financially unintelligent. They're
        financially underserved.
      </p>

      <p>
        The financial industry has spent decades making money sound
        complicated, partly because complication justifies fees. Most
        household money decisions are simpler than they look once
        someone calmly explains them.
      </p>

      <p>
        You don't have to wait until you've "fixed everything" to ask
        for help. Wherever you're starting is where we start.
      </p>

      <p>
        Permission matters. To spend on what you love. To wash a
        ziplock bag if it lets you fly first class once a year. To
        want what you want and plan for it in plain English.
      </p>

      <p>
        Calmness is the most underrated financial skill there is. You
        can do this. You don't need to panic.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section" aria-labelledby="audience-heading">
    <div class="column">
      <h2 id="audience-heading">Who Stacey works with</h2>

      <p>
        Stacey works mostly with women navigating a transition.
        Retirement. Divorce. Widowhood. A late start. Caring for
        aging parents while raising kids. A divorce that left more
        questions than answers. An inheritance that arrived
        unexpectedly. A new career or a country move.
      </p>

      <p>
        Most are women who have been smart and capable in every
        other part of their lives, but have never had someone sit
        down with them about money without an agenda.
      </p>

      <p>
        You don't need to have it figured out before you arrive
        &mdash; no spreadsheet, no documents the first time.
      </p>

      <p style="margin-top: 1.75rem;">
        <a href="/services" class="cta">See how Stacey works</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
